\chapter*{Chapter 8}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Chapter 8}

\section*{Unbiased models}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Unbiased models}

\subsection*{8.1 Motivating example}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{8.1 Motivating example}

The head of the secret service in a secret country calls you up in the middle of the night. ``My name is X, it's secret,'' he says, ``and I need your help investigating the network of Y's bodyguards. Alas,'' says X, ``I can't tell you who Y is either, as it's also a secret, and worse, very little is known about Y's bodyguards. The only information that we've got, after spending nearly a billion of taxpayers' money, is that there are $n$ bodyguards and $m$ connections among them. What would be the right model for such a network given all this top-secret information???'' asks X insistently.

You're clearly in shock, and not yet fully awaken, so you say (let $m < n$): ``just connect one bodyguard, a `captain', to $m$ others, like this:''

\begin{center}
\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\textit{[Figure: A network diagram showing a star-like structure. At the center is a node labeled ``captain'' in blue handwritten text with an arrow pointing to it. From this central node, multiple blue edges radiate outward connecting to approximately 8--9 peripheral nodes (shown as blue dots). The central captain node and all peripheral nodes are depicted as solid blue circles. The edges are drawn as blue lines forming a star topology where the captain is the hub and all other nodes are leaves connected only to the captain.]}
\end{figure}
\end{center}

\noindent \textbf{Q}uestions: Is your model ``correct''? Why? What could ``correct'' mean here at all?

\vfill

\begin{center}
33
\end{center}

\newpage

% ===== Page 2 =====
Answers: No, you were NOT given any information about any captain. He may simply not exist! There is no information that the network must be a star or have any hubs.

The model is not ``sufficiently random''; it is \emph{biased} to have a captain for no reason. You have to make it ``more random'', e.g. by connecting $m$ pairs of bodyguards selected out of $\binom{n}{2}$ possibilities uniformly at random:

\begin{center}
% \includegraphics[width=0.3\textwidth]{network_diagram}

\end{center}

\noindent\textbf{Q}: Is this $\mathcal{G}_{n,m}$?

\noindent\textbf{A}: It would be if nodes were labeled by $1, 2, ..., n$, but they are not! So it's ``unlabeled $\mathcal{G}_{n,m}$'', i.e. $\mathcal{U}_{n,m}$.

\noindent\textbf{Q}: What answer Biden expects if $n = 3$ and $m = 2$:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccc}
$P\left(\bullet\text{---}\bullet\text{---}\bullet\right) = 1$ & \textit{ok} & 
\begin{tabular}{l}
$P\left(\begin{array}{c}\bullet\text{---}\bullet\text{---}\bullet\end{array}\right) = {}^1\!/\!_3$ \\[0.5em]
$P\left(\begin{array}{c}\bullet\text{---}\bullet\text{---}\bullet\end{array}\right) = {}^1\!/\!_3$ \\[0.5em]
$P\left(\begin{array}{c}\bullet\text{---}\bullet\text{---}\bullet\end{array}\right) = {}^1\!/\!_3$
\end{tabular}
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\bigskip

\noindent\textbf{Main questions answered in the rest of this chapter:}

\begin{itemize}
\item If X expects a randomly labeled answer for whatever reason then is $\mathcal{G}_{n,m}$ ``sufficiently random''? Is there anything ``more random''?

\item If X needs an unlabeled answer, then what would that be? An unlabeled $\mathcal{G}_{n,m}$? What is it?
\end{itemize}

\vfill

\begin{center}
