\subsubsection*{8.3.3 \quad The difference between $\mathcal{G}(n,m)$ and $\mathcal{U}(n,m)$}

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
% \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{figure2}

\caption{The labeled, delabeled, and unlabeled microcanonical Erdős-Rényi random graphs of size $n=4$ with $m=2$ edges. The probabilities of all labeled graphs $G$ are the same $P(G) = 1/15$ in $\mathcal{G}_{4,2}$, while the probabilities of the symmetric and asymmetric unlabeled graphs $U_s$ and $U_a$ are different in the delabeled and unlabeled models $\mathcal{D}_{4,m}$ and $\mathcal{U}_{4,m}$.}
\end{figure}

\noindent
\textbf{Description of Figure 2:} The figure is divided into three horizontal sections, each representing a different model:

\textbf{Top section (Labeled $\mathcal{G}_{4,2}$):} Shows a blue-shaded box containing all 15 possible labeled graphs on 4 vertices with 2 edges. The graphs are arranged in a grid pattern, with vertices labeled 1, 2, 3, 4 and edges shown as lines connecting pairs of vertices. Each graph shows the vertex labels explicitly. The probability is stated as $P(G) = 1/15$ for each labeled graph.

\textbf{Middle section (Delabeled $\mathcal{D}_{4,2}$):} Shows a red-shaded box containing two unlabeled graph structures. The left structure $U_s$ represents a symmetric configuration (two disjoint edges) with probability $P(U_s) = 1/5$. The right structure $U_a$ represents an asymmetric configuration (two edges sharing a vertex) with probability $P(U_a) = 4/5$. A dashed horizontal line connects these two structures.

\textbf{Bottom section (Unlabeled $\mathcal{U}_{4,2}$):} Shows a green-shaded box containing the same two unlabeled graph structures $U_s$ and $U_a$. However, in this model, both structures have equal probability: $P(U_s) = 1/2$ and $P(U_a) = 1/2$. A dashed horizontal line connects these two structures.

The figure illustrates how the probability distributions differ between the delabeled model (which weights graphs by their automorphism group sizes) and the unlabeled model (which assigns uniform probability to each distinct unlabeled graph).

