% ===== Page 10 =====
\subsubsection{Connection between microcanonical and canonical ensembles}

Observe that since properties $f_s$ are the sufficient statistics in the canonical ensemble, then graphs with the same values of properties $f_s$ are equiprobable in the ensemble, so that it is a probabilistic mixture (a weighted sum) of microcanonical ensembles (uniform distribution):
\begin{equation}
P_{\text{can}}(G|\{f_s^*\}) = P_{\text{mic}}(G|\{f_s(G) = \phi_s\})\text{Prob}(\{f_s(G) = \phi_s\}|\{f_s^*\}) = \frac{1}{|\mathcal{G}(\{\phi_s\})|} P_{\text{can}}(\{\phi_s\}|\{f_s^*\}),
\tag{8.17}
\end{equation}

where, as before, $\mathcal{G}(\{\phi_s\})$ is the set of graphs whose values of properties $\{f_s\}$ are equal to $\{\phi_s\}$.

For example:
\begin{equation}
P_{\mathcal{G}(n,p)}(G|m^*) = p^{m(G)}(1-p)^{n'-m(G)} = \underbrace{P_{\mathcal{G}(n,m)}(G|m(G) = m)}_{\frac{1}{\binom{n'}{m}}} \underbrace{\text{Prob}(m(G) = m|m^*)}_{\text{Bin}[n',p](m) = \binom{n'}{m}p^m(1-p)^{n'-m}} \quad ,
\tag{8.18}
\end{equation}

where $p = m^*/n'$. Therefore, you can generate $G \sim \mathcal{G}(n,p)$ as follows:

1. sample $m \sim \text{Bin}[n',p]$,

2. sample $G \sim \mathcal{G}(n,m)$.

\vspace{10cm}

