% ===== Page 11 =====
\section{Hypercanonical ensemble}

\textbf{Definition 8.6.} A \textit{hypercanonical ensemble} is the probabilistic mixture of canonical ensembles with random $\{f_s^*\} \sim \rho$.

Therefore, to generate $G \sim P_{\text{hyp}}(\rho)$:

1. sample $\{f_s^*\} \sim \rho(\{f_s^*\})$,

2. sample $G \sim P_{\text{can}}(G|\{f_s^*\})$, either directly or:

(a) sample $\{\phi_s\} \sim P_{\text{can}}(\{\phi_s\}|\{f_s^*\})$

(b) sample $G \sim P_{\text{mic}}(G|\{\phi_s\})$

\textbf{Example} (in HW2): HER $\mathcal{G}(n, \rho)$: ER $\mathcal{G}(n, p)$ with random $p \sim \rho(p)$:

\begin{itemize}
\item let $\kappa \sim \text{Pareto}[\text{mean} = k > 0, \text{exponent } \gamma > 2]$, and $p = \min(1, \kappa/n)$;

\item show that in the $n \to \infty$ limit:
\begin{itemize}
\item in a given $G$ (``conditioned on $G$''), the degree distribution $P(k) = \text{Poisson}[\text{mean} = \kappa](k)$;
\item in the $\mathcal{G}(n, \rho)$ model, $P(k)$ is a power law with exponent $\gamma$.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

This is the simplest unbiased model of random graphs with a power-law degree distribution, even though almost all graphs have Poisson degree distributions, albeit with random means.

\textbf{Remember: degree distribution} $P(k) \neq$ \textbf{degree sequence distribution} $P(\{k_i\})$.

\section{Summary}

The canonical models considered in this chapter satisfy the basic niceness requirements: unbiasedness (maximum entropy) and the possibility to define typical graphs, thus providing a ``link'' between models and real data, and making statistical inference potentially useful.

